&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by OFTEC (HOT05)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Oil Firing T
[normal]echnical Association
[normal] (OFTEC) represents companies involved in the oil fired heating sector. Also it operates a Competent Persons scheme for
[normal] oil heating technicians licens
[normal]ed by the Department of Communities and Local Government and currently has some 8,700 persons on its regis
[normal]ter. For this function OFTEC is accredited by UKAS (No. 4371).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Background: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. 
[normal]Since 2008 OFTEC has been in discussions with DECC and its predecessor Departments about ways of reducing GHG emission from domestic oil boilers. It has promoted a new fuel kn
[normal]own as B30K which is a blend of kerosene (70%) with FAME 
[normal]biofuel
[normal] (30%). 
[normal]This fuel can be used in existing oil boilers after minor modifications to the boiler, and 
[normal]offers 
[normal]a
[normal] comparable 
[normal]heat output
[normal] and boiler efficiency
[normal] to that of kerosene.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However B30K 
[normal]has 
[normal]been excluded from the forthcoming domestic Renewable Heat Incentive
[normal] (RHI) 
[normal]in England and Wales, although it has been recognized for the Northern Ireland 
[normal]version of 
[normal]RHI. OFTEC believes that a bio-liquid such as B30K would make a significant contribution to
[normal] GHG reductions for rural homes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]DECC Heat Strategy (2013): 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]              
[normal]This strategy seeks to eliminate all fossil fuel usage for heat generation by 2050
[normal]. It envisages extensive 
[normal]use of de-carbonised electricity supplied through an enhanced 
[normal]electricity 
[normal]grid to
[normal] homes and buildings as the way to achieve this. OFTEC suggests that this 
[normal]policy 
[normal]is impractical 
[normal]in that it would require massive capital investment and therefore would impose 
[normal]high costs on energy consumers
[normal] which would be unacceptable politically. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]4.
[normal]              
[normal]A 
[normal]policy 
[normal]advoc
[normal]ated by the 
[normal]Heati
[normal]n
[normal]g
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]Hotwater
[normal] Industry 
[normal]Council (HHIC) 
[normal](
[normal]and others
[normal]) 
[normal]promotes a more “balanced transition” to low carbon heat. This should involve use of hybrid gas and oil condensing boilers working 
[normal]in tandem with h
[normal]eat pumps.
[normal] OFTEC supports t
[normal]he arguments made within the HHIC report entitled “Pathways for Domestic Heat”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Hybrid Heat technologies 
[normal]using oil: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. 
[normal]              
[normal]This
[normal] HHIC report sees a continuing role for oil and gas fire
[normal]d condensing boilers into the 
[normal]period 2025 -2030 because these technologies can work well with heat pumps in an 
[normal]auxiliary
[normal] role. 
[normal]The domestic RHI recogni
[normal]s
[normal]es this and allows payments for hybrid technologies providing that the renewable element of the heat is metered. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]              
[normal]OFTEC 
[normal]modelling
[normal] 
[normal]suggests that for an oil/Air 
[normal]Source
[normal] Heat
[normal] Pump (ASHP) hybrid boiler, (
[normal]assuming the ASHP has 
[normal]a Sea
[normal]sonal Performance Factor
[normal] - SPF -
[normal] of 2.5) 
[normal]the CO2 emissions for a 4 bed
[normal]room house would be 5.138 tonnes of 
[normal]C
[normal]O2 p.a. This compares with 6.302 
[normal]tonnes 
[normal]using an 
[normal]oil 
[normal]condensing boiler, and 4.756 tonnes using only 
[normal]the ASHP.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.
[normal]              
[normal]Whilst the CO2 emission
[normal]s
[normal] for the ASHP are slightly lower than 
[normal]for 
[normal]the hybrid, 
[normal]independent studies have shown that 
[normal]an 
[normal]ASHP 
[normal]working on its own 
[normal]cannot achieve high SPF in a sustained period of 
[normal]cold weather
[normal]. T
[normal]herefore 
[normal]it is 
[normal]un
[normal]likely that 
[normal]this leve
[normal]l of carbon output could 
[normal]be exceeded 
[normal]in a particularly cold year. 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Has the Government
[normal] made
[normal] the right ap
[normal]proach to reducing heat demand? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.
[normal]              
[normal]The Government’s flagship policy to reduce fossil fuel cons
[normal]umption in the domestic sector 
[normal]–
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]Renewable Heat Incentive - is unlikely to achieve its stated objectives. 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.
[normal]              
[normal]The domestic RHI is 
[normal]an 
[normal]innovative 
[normal]policy 
[normal]and does provide significant tax-payers funds to incentivi
[normal]s
[normal]e the switch to renewable heat. 
[normal]With an
[normal] estimated cost of £5.09 billion
[normal] and a net present value estimated at MINUS £1.836 billion 
[normal]over the policy Lifetime, 
[normal]this is an expensive policy
[normal]. 
[normal]The DECC Impact assessment (IA) forecasts (Table 8) that 579,000 homes will switch to renewable heat technolog
[normal]ies between 2014 and 2020 due to the RHI. However 
[normal]The Committee should
[normal] be aware that the 
[normal]same IA paper 
[normal]acknowledges that the uptake of the 
[normal]i
[normal]ncentive is unknown 
[normal](due to possible consumer indifference?) 
[normal]and says (
[normal]para
[normal] 77):
[normal] 
[normal]“however there is extreme uncertainty about how householders will make these investment decisions 
[normal]for renewable heating products.  …” 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]              
[normal]OFTEC suggests that the likelihood of many existin
[normal]g oil ho
[normal]useholds deciding to switch to 
[normal]renewable tech
[normal]nologies 
[normal]such
[normal] as ASHP, Ground Source Heat Pumps and B
[normal]io-mass (wood pellet) boilers is low. 
[normal]The principle reason for this is that nearly all decisions relating to a new heating system are made in emergency situations when a boiler breaks down and cannot be replaced. The
[normal] householder is desperate to have heating and hot water restored to their home and so makes a “distress purchase”. They do not have the time nor 
[normal]the 
[normal]money to consider a new technology which may require home adaptations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11. 
[normal]This fact
[normal] may explain some of t
[normal]he findings 
[normal]of a 
[normal]report c
[normal]ommissioned by DECC from 
[normal]Ipsos
[normal]/ 
[normal]MORI and the Energy Savings Trust en
[normal]titled 
[normal]“Homeowners’ Willingness 
[normal]To Take Up More Efficient Heating Systems
[normal]” (March 
[normal]2013)
[normal]. 
[normal]This surveyed 2,900 home owners and conducted a number of 
[normal]in-depth worksho
[normal]ps in the autumn of 2012. 
[normal]l
[normal]t
[normal] concluded: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We suggest that the Committee requests DECC for sight of this Report - if they have not done so already. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]C
[normal]ost of conversion to renewable heat:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12.
[normal]              
[normal]An earlier 
[normal]Impact Assessment (
[normal]IA
[normal])
[normal] for the RHI 
[normal](September 2012) 
[normal]stated
[normal] that 
[normal]38% (or 
[normal]145,000
[normal]) of the homes converting to renewable heat pre 2020 due to the RHI would be in 
[normal]rural 
[normal]areas. The latest IA puts the number converting to these new technologies at 579,000 which indicates that DECC
[normal] now forecast that 220,000 rural homes now will convert due to the RHI. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13.
[normal]              
[normal]OFTEC estim
[normal]ates that 80% 
[normal](176,000) 
[normal]of these will be homes using oil heating at present. 
[normal] 
[normal]The estimated capital costs of these conversions are shown in the table below, and the Co
[normal]mmittee will note that substantial up-front capital costs are involved installing Air Source Heat Pumps (ASHP), Ground Source Heat pumps (GSHP) and Wood Pellet Boilers (Pellet)
[normal]. Th
[normal]ese costs compare with approx
[normal].
[normal] £3,
[normal]0
[normal]00 
[normal]to replace an existing oil boiler with
[normal] a condensing oil boiler.
[normal] 
