[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Consumer r
[normal]esistance to Heat Pumps
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15.
[normal]              
[normal]Any heat strategy designed to reduce CO2 / GHG emissions from private homes must be
[normal] capable of being “sold” to home-owners. For the reasons stated above we 
[normal]believe that the currently 
[normal]favoured
[normal] technologies will be a hard sell. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]16.
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] 
[normal]favoured
[normal] technology – Air Source Heat Pumps –
[normal] should 
[normal]work well in new homes built to “zero carbon” stan
[normal]dards and with larger radiators and / or under
[normal]-
[normal]floor heating. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]17.
[normal]              
[normal]However heat pumps 
[normal]will not function effectively if they are fitted onto existing radiator systems and this has been acknowledged in the recent EST trials.
[normal] 
[normal]The full cost 
[normal]of installing an e
[normal]ffective heat pump 
[normal]in an exi
[normal]s
[normal]ting property s
[normal]hould include the cost of a new radiator 
[normal]or under-floor heating 
[normal]system. 
[normal]In addition good functionality 
[normal]of heat pumps 
[normal]requires 
[normal]properties 
[normal]to be 
[normal]fully insulated
[normal]. Many rural homes are older (pre-1914) and have solid
[normal] walls. The option of cavity wall insulation is not open to these homes and the alternative - solid wall insulation- is expensive, unproven and can be unsightly. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]18.
[normal]              
[normal]A further factor which should b
[normal]e noted regarding
[normal] heat pumps 
[normal]is that they 
[normal]do not provide 
[normal]“hot radiators” which can be used to 
[normal]warm yourself on when cold or to 
[normal]“dry the clothes”. Consumers are used to 
[normal]radiators doing this and 
[normal]there could be negative reaction to these perceived
[normal] shortcomings of renewable heat from some people.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ru
[normal]nning costs of preferred Renewable Technologies (pre-RHI)
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19.
[normal]              
[normal]The RHI is designed to compensate home owners for the capital costs of installing renewable heat and to contribute to their running costs for seven years. 
[normal]We note that 
[normal]within 
[normal]the 
[normal]RHI document 
[normal]issued on 12
[normal]th
[normal] July 20
[normal]13, the examples of what paymen
[normal]t
[normal]s
[normal] might be expected are based upon a building heat requirement of 15,000 kWh p.a. Due to the design of many rural homes, we submit that the average building heat
[normal] l
[normal]oss would be higher at aro
[normal]und 24,000 to
[normal] 28,000kWh p.a. Domestic 
[normal]RHI payments are based upon a deemed heat calculated from an energy performance 
[normal]assessment
[normal] and not from metering actual renewable heat emitted. We suggest that customers could 
[normal]be exposed to the risk of 
[normal]having 
[normal]high
[normal]er than anticipate
[normal]d
[normal] electricity bills due to heat pumps cycling on and off to meet 
[normal]high 
[normal]heating demand. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20.
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]future 
[normal]costs of electricity and wood pellets 
[normal]for the favoured RHI technologies are un
[normal]known
[normal]. Electricity prices are likely to rise to reflect 
[normal]the 
[normal]increased gene
[normal]rating costs for nuclear and wind-power. 
[normal]The Committee should note that the current average fuel costs 
[normal]p.a. 
[normal]in GB for a three bedroom house in the period July 2012 – July 2013 are set out below: 
